glosses: to infiltrate, to strain, filter, to separate solid from liquid by passing through a strainer or colander
to examine or observe carefully, eye

etymology:
Inherited from Ottoman Turkish سوزمك (süzmek, “to strain, filter, to examine carefully”), from Proto-Turkic *süŕ- (“to strain, filter”). Compare Hungarian szűr (“to strain, filter”), an early Turkic borrowing from the Bulgar language.
Akin to Proto-Mongolic *sür- (“to sprinkle”) (Mongolian шүрших (šüršix, “to spatter”)) and Proto-Tungusic *sir- (“to strain, press out, to milk”) (Evenki сир (sir, “to squeeze, milk”)).
Cognates
Cognate with Karakhanid [script needed] (süzmēk, “to filter, strain”), Old Uyghur [script needed] (süz-, “to filter, strain”), Azerbaijani süzmək (“to filter”), Bashkir һөҙөү (höźöw, “to strain”), Chagatai [script needed] (süzmek, “to purify, clarify”), Chuvash сӗрме (sĕrme, “to strain, filter, catch fish by a net”), Kazakh сүзу (süzu, “to strain, filter”), Kipchak [Arabic needed] (süz-), Kyrgyz сүзүү (süzüü, “to strain, filter”), Tatar сөзү (sözü, “to strain”), Tuvan сүзер (süzer, “to walk in water”), Turkmen süzmek (“to strain, filter”), Uyghur سۈزمەك (süzmek, “to filter, strain”), Uzbek suzmoq (“to strain, filter”).
